Consider code
```js
const x = {}
const y = new (function () {})
const z = new Error
x.prop = 'prop'
y.prop = 'prop'
z.prop = 'prop'

console.log( // shallow shorthand
  [x, y, z].map(
    _.iteratee({prop: 'prop'})
  )
) // [true, true, true] works as expected

console.log( // deep shorthand
  [{obj: x}, {obj: y}, {obj: z}].map(
    _.iteratee({obj: {prop: 'prop'}})
  )
) // [true, true, false] while should be [true, true, true]
```

This bug affects not only specific `interatee()` usage, but all other deep shorthands, because they are used `interatee` under the hood. E.g.:
```js
console.log(
  _.partition(
    [{obj: x}, {obj: y}, {obj: z}],
    {obj: {prop: 'prop'}}
  ) // [ [ { obj: [Object] }, { obj: [Object] } ], [ { obj: [Error] } ] ]
) // while should have all elements in first array
```
